  "prompt": "Can the parallelogram be a rhombus?",
  "response": "Yes, a parallelogram can be a rhombus. A rhombus is a special type of parallelogram where all four sides are of equal length. In addition to having opposite sides that are parallel and congruent (like all parallelograms), a rhombus also has the property that its diagonals bisect each other at right angles. So, all rhombuses are parallelograms, but not all parallelograms are rhombuses.",
